text: The tapes are on. Okay, so you wrote the Essex book. So yeah, could you kind of give us a general history of those, and then I'll hit on the specifics that you don't cover. Well, in the first place, I'd moved from Syracuse, New York, to Los Angeles District in 1965. And at that time, I was working as a tech writer for the space defense industry. And of course, I was writing on the side. I built up a good backlog of science fiction novels and short stories. But I hadn't become a full-time writer. Well, in 1969, a month before the first moon landing, NASA had its funds cut way back, and thousands of people working in the space industry were laid off, including myself. So I couldn't get a job there for a while, and finally I got one, and I said, I want to go into full-time writing, and I did. Well, shortly thereafter, though I had a lot of money coming in from my book publishers, I couldn't get it out of them. I guess they were going through one of those slumps where they were reluctant to let loose funds, and I needed some money. Well, at that time, I was approached by a fellow named Brian Kirby, who was a science fiction fan, but he also was an editor for a pornographic book publishing outfit, I think called American Art Agency. And he was starting a new line called Essex House. Although Brian had been an editor for some time in the porno field, he was pretty much disgusted with the books because, one, the writing level was very low, and there wasn't any characterization or plot or motivation, and very little imagination. And he wanted to raise the literary level of the porno books, I mean, at least the ones in the new line Essex House. He also loved science fiction, so he approached a number of science fiction authors, and asked them if they'd be interested. At that time, 1969, I'd never even read one of those books, unless you count Henry Miller as a porno writer, and I don't. And I said, yeah, I'm a writer, I'd like to try anything. I'll even write romances if I have to. So he said there would be no taboos or guidelines. Normally, in the porno books, they have guidelines, and that you have to have a sex scene every four or five, six pages. He said you can write it exactly the way you want to. So I decided that I would write a satirical pastiche on my two heroes, one Tarzan and one the Hero of Pope magazine series, which started in the 30s, called Doc Savage. Doc Savage is pretty well known even now, because Bantam started reprinting his books in 1965. So I wrote that, and I had a lot of fun with it. And it went out where, I didn't know. And then I wrote a book called The Image of the Beast, which was sort of a satire on gothics and also on private eye novels, and incidentally, it was a satire on porno books, too. So that went out, and then I wrote a sequel called Blown, a sequel to The Image of the Beast. And about that time, I got kind of tired. I guess even if you have a vivid imagination, there's only so much that you can do with books that are basically sexual situations. And though I gave it my best, I had characterization and humor and plot and motivation and all that, I got tired of it, so I ceased writing for them. And about that time, my publishers started coming through with all the money they'd owed me anyway. Now, what happened was that the people who ran the American Art Agency knew nothing whatsoever about science fiction. And all they knew was porno books. So they made the very bad mistake of sending all these science fiction books, which I and some other science fiction readers had threatened, to the porno bookshops, not to the general bookstores. And as a result, they didn't sell well, because the usual porno customer wasn't interested in them. And by the time that the science fiction people heard that these books were available, the American Art Agency had already decided to cancel Ethics House. It wasn't a financial go for them, but it was their own fault. Well, I don't know how many of these three books that I wrote were printed. I do know that at one time I was told there were hundreds or maybe even thousands in a warehouse in Los Angeles. But I've never been able to find out if they're still there or what, because the American Art Agency closed up a couple of years ago. And I've had no success in getting a hold of the person who's handling the estate. Is that enough, or do you want to ask me questions? No, that sounds good. Does it surprise you that the books are now considered to be top-end collector's items in command? Oh, I've seen them anywhere from $75 to $150 a piece. Did that ever enter your mind? Well, it never entered my mind at the time I wrote them. If I had, I would have kept the copies that Brian Kirby gave me. As it was, I just passed them out to friends here and there. And as a result, I only have about one or two samples of each of them. If I'd known what was going to happen, I would have purchased three or four boxfuls myself. When word got around, of course, collectors being what they are, they look for rare and unusual books, and they had difficulty finding them. So, of course, the price went up right away, and it's been going up steadily since then. Another aspect of that was that after the American Art Agency folded, I got my rights back to the books, and then I tried to sell them to a national publisher. But I didn't have any success for ten years. Nobody would touch them. And then finally, Playboy Press decided to publish them, and Granada in England decided that they would do it. Also another publisher, I forget their name. The English publishers were taking a chance because they were afraid they would be bought to court as it happened. They got by okay. And now, of course, why the books are, in comparison with other books dealing with sex, they're not, well, I wouldn't exactly call them innocuous, but their far-ranging sexual ideas are not so much, they can't be accepted now. Back in 69 and 70, when I wrote them, my national publisher is just afraid to pick a chance with them. I always thought that the Doc Caliban character on the front of A Feast Unknown looked kind of like you. The hair and the general facial features, is that just coincidence? Well, it probably is, unless Brian Kirby described me to the artist, which he could have done. I never thought about it told truth. It's kind of a last gasp there. Now, you wrote, Lord of the Trees and the Mad Goblin are clean sequels to A Feast Unknown. And did you just kind of do those to, or just to keep up with the fun, the pastiche type writing? Yeah, that was the main thing. The thing was, of course, in the Feast Unknown, my two heroes, Doc Caliban and Lord Gibbertson, were engaged in eliminating this ancient evil Council of Nine. And they'd only knocked off a few in the first book, so I wanted to continue their adventures, which I did in the Mad Goblin and the Lord of the Trees. And they succeeded in eliminating a few more of the Council of Nine. However, there are still some left, so I plan on writing at least one sequel to those and finishing up the job. Although I don't know when I'm going to do it. You know, actually, I have about 15 theories going, none of which I've ever finished. Well, when I was young and went to a psychologist while I was attending the University of Missouri, he commented that I had terrible difficulty in finishing anything. So we'll look forward to seeing some more of those then. Well, I hope so. I had a lot of fun writing them. And I didn't continue the sexual theme in them. In the first place, I think I exhausted them in the first two books. In the second place, it's difficult to get publishers to accept them if you do have that theme there. A less obvious sequel to me was Traitor to the Living as a sequel to Blown. It seems like it was a little more subtle there that that might be a sequel. Is it a sequel? Can it be considered a sequel? Oh, yeah, it's a sequel. I think some of the readers weren't aware of it at the time. Actually, that's why it opened for another sequel, too, you know. Good. I enjoyed it. Okay, what about Love Song, then? That was Brandon House. Are they connected with Essex House, or how did that come about? Well, I guess I was... Yeah, okay. I wrote that about the time I decided I wasn't going to do it anymore, but I already had a contract. So I wrote it. It was not science fiction. It sounded like a gothic, but it had a rational explanation at the end. That's even a rarer book than The Feast Unknown, Image of the Beast, and Blown. So I've noticed. Very difficult to get a hold of. So, again, I only have one copy. Now, it has not been reprinted anywhere, has it? No. I wanted to write in to whoever was handling the estate and get their rights back. Unfortunately, I can't find him. This wasn't Brian Kirby and Essex House, that Brandon House is something different? It was... Brandon House was a line that had existed before Essex House. But when Essex House ceased, then Brian Kirby went back to Brandon House, which he was with before he started Essex House. And that was done with him. Although by the time I'd finished the book, if I remember correctly, Brian Kirby had already left American Art Agency. If I can ever find the guy that's handling the business, I'll get the rights back to that and see if this reprinted. But for all I know, he died or he's in hiding for the police or went to Brazil or something. Okay. While we're still in the gutter here, in the book by a guy named Lawrence Knapp called the First Editions of Philip Jose Farmer, he says that you wrote a book called As You Desire with the pseudonym William Norfolk. Is that true? Yeah, that's true. But what happened was I wrote that. A friend of mine who's working for another house came down and I was still still needed still needed money. And I agreed with with him to write it, but I said I wanted to do it under an nom de plume. So I sent the manuscript in. I don't remember offhand the name of the house that took it. And for years I thought that they'd published it, but just had never bothered to send me a copy. However, I found out in the last couple of years that they had gone under. And they'd sold all their manuscripts to the American Art Agency, which also went under. So the original manuscript was in possession of the American Art Agency in some warehouse up in North Hollywood. So for the collectors that are going to be reading this, yes, you did write it, but it has never been released as a book. No. I do have a carbon in the manuscript, but I've made no effort to send it out. Well, in light of all the meanings and subtleties to the pseudonyms that you use, is there anything to the nom de plume William Norfolk? Well, there's usually something symbolic or significant in the nom de plumes that I take over. But this was the first time I ever did something under another name, and there wasn't any particular significance attached to that, except that they said if you had MD after the title, it seemed to attract more readers. Of course, I didn't say what MD stood for. It could have been Doctor of Madness. That sounds apropos. Yeah, well, at the time I was thinking about choosing the pseudonym. I happened to be reading Burke's Courage, and I was reading about the Duke of Norfolk. Oh, Norfolk, that's a good name. Can you give us just a very brief outline? Is that a science fiction book or a fantasy book or just a mainstream book or what? No, it again is a porno-gothic romance, I'd call it. It has to do with lesbianism and also spooky houses and ghosts and all that sort of stuff. Okay. My manuscript is a real collector's item because I'm the only one that has it. I haven't gotten any offers for it yet, and I probably wouldn't sell it, but as years go by, it becomes more valuable. It might make up for all those collector's items I gave away. Okay, yeah, maybe you can retire on that since you did. Well, I doubt if I could retire on it. Okay, what we want to do is change our cassette tape over to the other side, and then we'll start talking about Oz. Now, what I'm going to do, Mr. Farmer, is send this to Fred Greenberg in New Jersey, and he's going to transcribe it, and we're going to use this in his paperback advertiser. If you would like copies of that, I'd be glad to send you some when it comes out. Oh, yeah, I would for my bibliography. You bet. There will be several of them. My address? Pardon me? Do you have my address? Yes, sir, I do. I don't know. I think it'll probably be one or two months, but I have the four Essex, well, the three Essex in the branded books, so we took pictures of them, and we'll have pictures in there just so people can see what they look like. Oh, okay. I was kind of glad to hear that As You Desire hadn't come out because I don't have it, and I've got everything else you did in the first edition, so I thought I was going to have to go looking for it. Well, maybe someday I might rewrite it in the command that comes out. Okay. I just got through rereading. We're still rewinding here. I just got through reading the Purple Book. I enjoyed that. I'd read the New Writers of the Purple Wage, but I hadn't read the others, and I enjoyed that. Oh, thank you. I had a lot of fun writing The Making of Revelation Part 1 and also Purple Passage of Rip Van Winkle. Yeah, I would think you would have enjoyed that. Okay, are we rewound and are we turned over? The tape's rolling. Okay, the tape's rolling, so we'll start talking about Oz now in light of your Barnstormer and Oz. Did you read the Oz books when you were a child or as a young adult? Oh, I started reading them when I was very young. I think about six or seven years old. Our local library here in Peoria, the Branch Library, had all the books by Bowne, and I loved them and read and reread them. And then a couple, about two years ago, I joined the International Wizard of Oz Club, which is composed of people who are devoted to Bowne's works, and they put out a quarterly called the Bowne Bugle. I also went out and repurchased all of Bowne's books. I had a collection, but they were destroyed in a flash flood in Los Angeles while I was there. And then I got all the Oz books by Ruth Plumlee Thompson, who continued the series after Bowne died. And I have books by Oz books by several other people, Jack Snow, also Neil, who illustrated the Bowne books, wrote a couple. And I'd always had a desire, ever since I was young, to be a writer, and I'd always wanted to write an Oz book. But I didn't get around to it until I was 64 years old. Now, of course, the book that I would write when I'm 64 is quite different from the one that I would write if I were 10 or 11. So I'm waiting to hear the reaction from the members of the International Wizard of Oz Club. Because this, as you know, assumes that only the first Oz book, The Wonderful Wizard of Oz, is true. And that's all the rest are fiction. And then it approaches Oz from a science fictional viewpoint. That is, it could have existed if it did, then you have to explain how a scarecrow could be animated and sentient and talk. What would happen if animals could talk? How do you account for the 10 woodman's piecemeal method of being reconstructed out of 10? and explain magic and explain magic and all that sort of stuff from just where Oz was. I had a lot of fun doing it, but I also had to do an awful lot of research because it took place in 1923 and I had to read all about what was happening in America at that time. and I've been a World War I and early aviation buff and I have a considerable library on that, but I still had to look up a lot of things on the Jennings and on the machine guns and the BARs of that period and army organization, politics, and all that sort of thing. plus, of course, the agonizing task of being able to explain in a rational manner just how the land of Oz could exist and how all these beings could exist in it. Also, there's something you may not have noticed. There's a character in there called Sharts the Shirtless. Okay. And he actually is sort of a wild Doc Savage. If you were acquainted with the first Doc Savage magazine that came out, you would see that his shirt was torn to shreds. And the, when the 1965 reissues by Bantam came out, the artist, what was his name? Hmm. I can't remember it right off right hand. But anyway, he continued that torn shirt motif. So, Sharts, the shirtless, is sort of an Ozziean takeoff on Doc Savage. Plus the fact that his rare, his companion, the rare beast logo, is sort of a takeoff on Doc Savage's apish buddy, Monk Mayfair. It doesn't matter to the reader whether he knows that or not, but if he does know it, it adds a little extra savor. I didn't catch that. When I read it, I figured there was something there, but I haven't read everything yet, and one of the things I have not read is Doc Savage, and so I don't get those subtle points. Well, that's all right. That's just something I add in case you do happen to know it. Fine, but Sharts, the shirtless, and the rare beast stand out by themselves as characters. Anyway, I departed at a 90 degree angle from the original model. When I make the shows based on this tape, I'm going to put that in because that's one of the things that makes this fun to find out things like that. I guess if you hadn't arbitrarily, well, I guess not arbitrarily, but if you hadn't cut it off after the first volume and said everything thereafter was fantasy, the task of writing it would have been that much more complicated. Well, it would have been impossible because Baum's books had so many changes and contradictions in them later on that it would be impossible to explain. Plus the fact that if you are writing an original Oz novel, you can do it without getting permission from people who own the copyright because the first two books have gone out of copyright. I ascertained that before I thought about or thought seriously about starting to write on them. I wrote to Riley Company in Chicago and they told me that if I could go ahead and write an Oz novel, as long as I did not use any new characters or places in the later books, that is those that were written after the first two, if they contained new characters, let's say like the Hungry Tiger, where are we in, maybe use in a second, well anyway, there were a number of characters like the Gnome King that I could not have used because they were in the later books. but the main thing was, of course, obviously, the later books were fiction. I mean, there were so many contradictions and changes. Why was Oz so popular? I guess it was almost an instant success and a continuance, and it still is popular. Why do you think that those books are so popular? Well, of course, there were many books written back in 1900 and afterwards about foreign lands or fairy lands, but what Baum did was to create a magnificent quest, and what you have Dorothy looking for a way of getting home, the cowardly lion, wanting courage, ten woodmen running a heart, and a scarecrow running brain. Now, the thing is, they all thought that the wonderful Wizard of Oz could give it to them. Well, he told them he would, but he put them through a series of trials. You know, first they had to go out and kill the wicked witch of the West, and I forget offhand what the other quest was. But the point was that they had all these qualities that they wanted. The scarecrow was ignorant, but he was intelligent, and the ten woodmen had a very tender heart, even if he didn't have a heart inside that ten body. And the carly lion was like all of us. He'd get scared, but he was able to overcome his fear. But they needed some magical reassurance, and finally when they exposed the Wizard of Oz as a humbug, he still concocted devices, physical devices, which were symbols of what they wanted. You know, he had the cowardly lion drink a pot of courage. Somebody had suggested it was probably Dutch courage. And he made a heart out of velvet filled with sawdust and put it inside the ten woodman's body. he stuck, oh, okay. He put bran inside the scarecrow's head, and then he put needles in them, and he said his head was brand new now, and it was sharp, needle sharp, of course. The bowel was great for fun. And having these physical evidence of things they wanted, they proceeded to be very happy, although they'd had these qualities all this time. And I think that moral there, that wonderful quest that found both for them, was something that appealed to the hearts of all the kids, and of course adults too. And then, of course, Dorothy had had the means of getting home all the time, because when the Wicked Witch of the East was crushed by her house, dropping out of the cyclone, she put on the silver slippers of the witch, and wore them all through her adventure, not knowing that all she had to do was wish to be back in Kansas, and she could go home. It wasn't until Glenda the Good, at the end of the book, told her that her shoes could do it, that Dorothy realized that all this time, she could have gone home a few minutes after she got into odds if she wanted to. In other words, Baum was saying, well, look, look around you, maybe you have the means for success or escape around you, you don't have to find some magical means. Although, of course, the silver slippers were magical. Well, anyway, that's my explanation of the popularity of the book. And, of course, there are millions who, I suppose, never read the book, who know about Oz through the movie. in a barnstormer of eyes, the character that interested me most, it seemed to be the character you were most into was Glenda the Good or Glenda the Ambiguous. Yeah. My good. Okay. She was an interesting character. Yeah, well, I sort of fell in love with Glenda when I was little. and, of course, now being almost 65, I have sort of an adult viewpoint of Oz. I can still enjoy it in an almost childlike manner, but now being an adult, I can see that there are profundities in three dimensions to that. Then it came to me that perhaps all these adventures that Dorothy had gone through had been sort of subtly arranged. by Glenda in order to knock off one, the Witches of the East and two, the Witches of the West and also get rid of the Wizard, whom she knew was a humbug. So I became very much interested in her character. And then I thought, hmm, President Harding died in 1923. Did Glenda have anything to do with that? Are you going to blame the Depression on her in a sequel maybe? No, I hadn't thought about that. Oh, that's a good idea. I had somebody else responsible for it. You know, peace. When you wrote Barnstormer, what audience were you aiming for? Science fiction audience. Although, of course, there are a lot of people who don't read much science fiction who still like Oz. But primarily, I think I was writing it for myself. I mean, you know, you get down to the bottom of it. Because I've always loved Oz. Always wanted to write an Oz book and finally did it. There's always more, there are always more wonders there, you know. I might write one more. maybe four or five years from now. That was going to be my next question. It seemed that it didn't end abruptly, but nonetheless, there were a few things that the reader, I think, would like to know about. So it would be appreciated if you continued it. I was under a lot of pressure to get the manuscript in and time. But I could use that in the sequel, for instance, because I had a pretty interesting scene sketched out in my mind. And there are a lot of other things. Well, yeah, I'd think of... It's a science fiction book. I took what Baum had set out and then I tried to extrapolate it, extrapolate from it, go deeper. A lot of things that Baum, who was writing a fairy tale for children, just glossed over, which he should have done, because children aren't interested in great detail. But the background that Baum furnished, and I had to go ahead and figure out just what kind of society would have existed in us. And, for instance, the effect of intelligent language-speaking animals, what would that have on society? Certainly our society would not be much like Earth society, for instance. Just because of the presence of those animals. Just like you had almost as if you had extraterrestrial people living among you, with whom you have to deal, you know, and strike some sort of social balance. I was also struck by the explanation for the purpose of scarecrows in Oz. That was a complete switch, right? If crows have the intelligence of human beings and can talk, they're not going to be fooled one minute by a scarecrow, right? But Dorothy had assumed, because of her short stay there, that scarecrows were up there for the purpose they were set up for on Earth. So I figured out otherwise. the other interesting reaction that I had was when I read the scene in which the pilot of the first mission that tried to make it through when the pilot was killed, when they buried him and they had this barbaric funeral ritual. That was kind of interesting as well. Well, Oz is not a mamby-pamby land. It's real and inhabited by real people, even if they're very short people. And if you have people who are descended from the ancient gods who intermingled with the Neanderthals originally, then you're not going to have a society quite like the medieval societies of earth. There would be a lot of customs that would be different. And like all societies, even Oz society, you know, has its sinister aspects, its frightening aspects, its alien aspects. So I'll go into more depth on that in the sequel, or possibly when I write that quaddling translation of The Wizard of Oz, I might go into that in the forward. Have you gotten any feedback from either Fred Meyer or the people in the International Wizard of Oz fan club, or just any Oz fans in general? Yeah, I got a letter from a Nick Korolenko, who apparently has done some movie work too. And he even wrote a documentary on Oz once, which Disney didn't take because they said they wanted to take a different direction. But he still has hopes of producing it someday. And he loved it. And as a matter of fact, he's going to call me up for a second for an interview, it should be printed in the Bound Bugle, I believe. Oh, good. Okay. It'll be accompanying a review of the book. Okay. Fred Meyer sent me a copy of the Bound Bugle, which I had not seen before. And it had all sorts of things about the history of Oz as a stage play and that sort of thing. It was really interesting. I didn't realize it had that much background. Oh, yeah. The Wizard of Oz Club takes a very scholarly approach to everything. And they've really gone into all of Baum's works in great depth. I'm not really an I guess I am kind of a fan. I never would have read it except I have a daughter who's now five. And I guess I'm in volume 10. I'm reading her a chapter a night. And so I was, I of course had seen the movie. But I really enjoyed A Barnstormer because I had read the first one and I could understand why you chose not to go into the rest of it and treated them as fantasy because of all the things. But it's really enjoyable to see it, to read it myself and then to see it through her eyes because she obviously sees it on a different level. Yeah, well, I'm glad you're doing that. I'm starting off my granddaughter on the Oz books. And I hope that she'll have the same enthusiasm that I had for her. The only thing I do, sometimes the English gets a bit antiquated, so I maybe modernize it just a little bit just so she'll know what the guy's really doing. Well, I can understand that. She's five. He's climbing the stairs. He's not ascending the whatever. Five-year-olds don't quite get all the flowery language sometimes. Yeah, but later on when she starts reading herself, you know, she'll be able to tackle it without any difficulties. Mr. Farmer, that's it. I do appreciate getting to talk to you about this. Well, I'm glad to do it. Great. I enjoyed meeting you in June in Dallas. I didn't have my copy of Love Song then, so I'll have to go to a con where you're at one of these days and get it signed. Well, you could always mail it to me. I can mail it back. Okay, I may do that. Better insure it, though, and make sure it on. Okay, I'll do that. Okay, I would appreciate that. I might take you up on that. Yeah. Okay, again, thanks very much. It's been very enjoyable and look forward to seeing whatever it is that you put out next. It's always a pleasure to read it. Okay. Take care, Mr. Farmer. Good night now.
